{{Discrimination sidebar|expand-social=yes}}
'''Discrimination against drug addicts''' is a form of [[discrimination]] against people who suffer from a [[drug addiction]]. 

In the process of [[stigmatization]], drug addicts are [[stereotype]]d as having a particular set of undesirable traits, in turn causing other individuals to act in a [[fear]]ful or [[prejudicial]] manner toward them.<ref name="Stigma of addiction part I 2017 review">{{cite journal | vauthors = Corrigan P, Schomerus G, Shuman V, Kraus D, Perlick D, Harnish A, Kulesza M, Kane-Willis K, Qin S, Smelson D | title = Developing a research agenda for understanding the stigma of addictions Part I: Lessons from the Mental Health Stigma Literature | journal = The American Journal on Addictions | volume = 26 | issue = 1 | pages = 59–66 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27779803 | doi = 10.1111/ajad.12458 | quote = Social psychologists have distinguished the largely private experience of stigma in general—stereotypes and prejudice—from the more public, behavioral result which is discrimination.[11] Stereotypes are harmful and disrespectful beliefs about a group. Table 1 lists several examples of stereotypes applied to people with addictions including blame, dangerousness, and unpredictability. }}</ref><ref name="Stigma of addiction part II 2017 review">{{cite journal | vauthors = Corrigan PW, Schomerus G, Shuman V, Kraus D, Perlick D, Harnish A, Kulesza M, Kane-Willis K, Qin S, Smelson D | title = Developing a research agenda for reducing the stigma of addictions, part II: Lessons from the mental health stigma literature | journal = The American Journal on Addictions | volume = 26 | issue = 1 | pages = 67–74 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27875626 | doi = 10.1111/ajad.12436 }}</ref><ref name="Health professional prejudice and discrimination 1996 review">{{cite journal | vauthors = McLaughlin D, Long A | title = An extended literature review of health professionals' perceptions of illicit drugs and their clients who use them | journal = Journal of Psychiatric and Mental Health Nursing | volume = 3 | issue = 5 | pages = 283–8 | date = October 1996 | pmid = 9004621 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2850.1996.tb00127.x }}</ref>

== Background ==
{{transcluded section|source=Discrimination}}
{{trim|{{#section-h:Discrimination|Drug use}}}}

=== Individual factors ===
Drugs (especially [[opioid]]s and [[stimulant]]s) can change the motivational patterns of a person and lead to [[desocialization]] and degradation of personality.<ref>Chen, Lingjun, Xinyin Chen, Siman Zhao, Doran C French, Shenghua Jin, and Ling Li. "Predicting Substance Use and Deviant Behavior from Prosociality and Sociability in Adolescents." Journal of youth and adolescence 48, no. 4 (2019): 744–752.</ref> Acquisition of the drugs sometimes involves [[black market]] activities, exposing users to social circles engaging in other criminal behavior.<ref>Frauger, Elisabeth, Sandra Nordmann, Veronica Orleans, Vincent Pradel, Vanessa Pauly, Xavier Thirion, and Joëlle Micallef. "Which Psychoactive Prescription Drugs Are Illegally Obtained and through Which Ways of Acquisition? About OPPIDUM Survey." Fundamental & clinical pharmacology 26, no. 4 (2012): 549–556.</ref> Certain types of criminal behavior can also put drug users at further risk of harm, or lead to additional stigmatization ([[sex work]], [[drug dealing]], [[theft]], [[robbery]], etc.).<ref>Surratt, Hilary L, James A Inciardi, Steven P Kurtz, and Marion C Kiley. "Sex Work and Drug Use in a Subculture of Violence." Crime and delinquency 50, no. 1 (2004): 43–59.</ref>

=== Institutional basis ===

Stigma by health care professionals stems from a belief that people with substance use disorder are not interested in their health as much as they are seeking drugs. This results in people with substance use disorders receiving unfair medical care. As well as hiding their underlying medical concerns and not receiving the medical and recovery care that is needed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Livingston |first1=James D |last2=Milne |first2=Teresa |last3=Fang |first3=Mei Lan |last4=Amari |first4=Erica |title=The effectiveness of interventions for reducing stigma related to substance use disorders: a systematic review |journal=Addiction |date=2012 |volume=107 |issue=1 |pages=39–50 |doi=10.1111/j.1360-0443.2011.03601.x |pmid=21815959 |pmc=3272222 }}</ref> Healthcare providers have effective tools such as medications for opioid and alcohol addiction that can help prevent many overdoses. These tools are not used widely in the United States healthcare system. The stigma that surrounds drug addicts is the main cause of why the healthcare system does not use these tools and medications. In the United States healthcare system there has not been much done to remove this stigmatism. Many healthcare providers do not view addiction as a disease and a mental illness.<ref name="National Institute on Drug Abuse">{{cite web |last1=Volkow |first1=Nora |title=Addressing the Stigma that Surrounds Addiction |url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/about-nida/noras-blog/2020/04/addressing-stigma-surrounds-addiction |website=National Institute on Drug Abuse |date=22 April 2020 |publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse |access-date=16 November 2020 |ref=46}}</ref>

The drugs Ritalin ([[methylphenidate]]) and Adderall ([[amphetamine]]) are stimulants often prescribed for ADHD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://childmind.org/article/understanding-adhd-medications/|title = Understanding ADHD Medications}}</ref> In colleges there has been an influx of this type of drug trafficked. These drugs stimulate the nervous system, causing wakefulness and attentiveness. Prescribing opioids to patients and related overdose has become a serious problem in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/us-opioid-epidemic|title=The U.S. Opioid Epidemic}}</ref>

==== Lack of objective information about drugs ====
An important role in the process of discrimination is played by the lack of objective information about drug addiction and drug addicts, caused by legislative barriers to scientific research and the displacement of such information by [[propaganda]] of various kinds.<ref>{{cite web|author=П. Мейлахс|date=2003|title=Опасности моральной паники по поводу наркотиков|trans-title=The danger of moral panic about drugs|url=http://credonew.ru/content/view/324/28/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124106/http://credonew.ru/content/view/324/28/|archive-date=2019-02-09|access-date=2017-12-22|publisher=Кредо-Нью|language=ru}}</ref>

Drug addiction has been categorized as a subcategory of mental illness.<ref>{{cite web|date=2016|title=Addiction & Mental Illness: Does One Cause the Other?|url=https://www.dualdiagnosis.org/addiction-mental-illness-one-cause/|work=Dual Diagnosis|publisher=Foundations Recovery Network|vauthors=O'Leary D}}</ref> They are referred to as co-occurring disorders, which means that if a person is dealing with an addiction, they may also struggle with a mental illness.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Taylor MF, Coall D, Marquis R, Batten R|date=December 2016|title=Drug addiction is a scourge on the earth and my grandchildren are its victims: The tough love and resilient growth exhibited by grandparents raising the children of drug-dependent mothers.|journal=International Journal of Mental Health and Addiction|volume=14|issue=6|pages=937–51|doi=10.1007/s11469-016-9645-7|s2cid=38102148}}</ref> Most individuals who suffer from drug dependency are nearly twice as likely to suffer from a mental illness as well.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Proudfoot|first1=Jesse|date=July 2017|title=Drugs, addiction, and the social bond|url=http://dro.dur.ac.uk/21715/1/21715.pdf|journal=Geography Compass|volume=11|issue=7|pages=e12320|doi=10.1111/gec3.12320}}</ref> According to the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, about 8.9 million adults who have an addiction also have a psychiatric disorder. When dealing with either a mental illness or a drug addiction some symptoms people will experience are being incapable of controlling their own impulses and mood swings.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Canbolat F, Kul A, Özdemï M, Atïk U, Aydini A, Özden ST, Tarhan KN|date=December 2017|title=Substance Abuse Profiles of Patients Admitted to the Alcohol and Drug Addiction Research, Treatment, and Education Center in Turkey.|journal=Turkish Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences|volume=14|issue=3|pages=294–303|doi=10.4274/tjps.50470|pmc=7227934|pmid=32454628|doi-access=free}}</ref>

When a person falls victim to drug addiction, they will undergo the five stages of addiction which are the first use, the continued use, tolerance, dependence, and addiction.<ref name="pmid280014582">{{cite journal|vauthors=Wang Z, Li WX, Zhi-Min L|date=March 2017|title=Similarity and Difference in Drug Addiction Process Between Heroin- and Methamphetamine-Dependent Users|journal=Substance Use & Misuse|volume=52|issue=4|pages=459–467|doi=10.1080/10826084.2016.1245331|pmid=28001458|s2cid=3649040}}</ref> The first use stage, is the stage where individuals experiment with drugs and alcohol.<ref>Kopak, Albert M, and Norman G Hoffmann. "Pathways Between Substance Use, Dependence, Offense Type, and Offense Severity." Criminal justice policy review 25, no. 6 (2014): 743–760.</ref> This is the stage where individuals may partake in drug use due to curiosity, peer pressure, emotional problems among other reasons.<ref>Terry-McElrath, Yvonne M, Patrick M O'Malley, and Lloyd D Johnston. "Reasons for Drug Use Among American Youth by Consumption Level, Gender, and Race/Ethnicity: 1976–2005." Journal of drug issues 39, no. 3 (2009): 677–713.</ref> In the continued use stage, individuals know how the drug makes them feel and are likely to notice that they are not getting high as quickly as they use too.<ref>Pollini, Robin A, Thomas P O'Toole, Daniel Ford, and George Bigelow. "Does This Patient Really Want Treatment? Factors Associated with Baseline and Evolving Readiness for Change Among Hospitalized Substance Using Adults Interested in Treatment." Addictive behaviors 31, no. 10 (2006): 1904–1918.</ref> In the tolerance stage, the brain and the body have adjusted to the drug and it takes longer to get the effect an individual is seeking.<ref name=":13">{{Cite journal|last=Siegel|first=Shepard|title=Drug Tolerance, Drug Addiction, and Drug Anticipation|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|year=2005|volume=14|issue=6|pages=296–300|doi=10.1111/j.0963-7214.2005.00384.x|s2cid=145068335|issn=0963-7214}}</ref> Tolerance arrives after a period of continued use and is one of the first warning signs of addiction.<ref name=":13" /> In the dependence stage, the brain becomes accustomed to the drug and does not function well without it.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kandel|first=Denise B.|title=Stages and pathways of drug involvement examining the gateway hypothesis|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=1-107-12100-0|oclc=1162216007}}</ref> Substance abusers become physically ill without the use of drugs and will begin to develop symptoms of withdrawal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Emmett-Oglesby|first=M W|title=Animal Models of Drug Withdrawal Symptoms|date=April 1992|journal=Behavioural Pharmacology|volume=3|issue=Supplement|pages=32|doi=10.1097/00008877-199204001-00093|issn=0955-8810}}</ref>  In the addiction stage, individuals may struggle to discontinue use of drugs even if they do not enjoy it or if their behavior has caused problems within their lives.<ref>''Introducing Relapse Prevention / National Institute on Drug Abuse.'' Rockville, Md.: National Institutes of Health ; National Institute on Drug Abuse, 1993.</ref>

With the increasing number of adults that suffer from an addiction, only a few will receive treatment due to the complexity of health care systems.<ref name="pmid282528922">{{cite book|author1=Substance Abuse Mental Health Services Administration (US)|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK424857/|title=Facing Addiction in America: The Surgeon General's Report on Alcohol, Drugs, and Health|author2=Office of the Surgeon General (US)|series=Reports of the Surgeon General|date=November 2016|publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services|pmid=28252892}}</ref> Most health care systems do not have insurance coverage for addiction recovery and many health care providers have little to no training in treating addiction.<ref>Biancarelli, Dea L, Katie B Biello, Ellen Childs, M Drainoni, Peter Salhaney, Alberto Edeza, Matthew J Mimiaga, Richard Saitz, and Angela R Bazzi. "Strategies Used by People Who Inject Drugs to Avoid Stigma in Healthcare Settings." Drug and alcohol dependence 198 (2019): 80–86.</ref> Some doctors do not feel comfortable treating addictions, due to their lack of knowledge and training of the topic.<ref>Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration. (2018). Key substance use and mental health indicators in the United States: Results from the 2017 National Survey on Drug Use and Health (HHS Publication No. SMA 18-5068, NSDUH Series H-53). Rockville, MD: Center for Behavioral Health Statistics and Quality, Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration. Retrieved from <nowiki>https://www.samhsa.gov/data/</nowiki></ref> The American Society of Addiction Medicine reports that there are only 3,000 board-certified addiction specialist physicians in the United States while there are nearly 2 million people experiencing opioid addiction.<ref>Langabeer, James R, Angela L Stotts, Bentley J Bobrow, Henry E Wang, Kimberly A Chambers, Andrea J Yatsco, Marylou Cardenas-Turanzas, and Tiffany Champagne-Langabeer. "Prevalence and Charges of Opioid-Related Visits to U.S. Emergency Departments." Drug and alcohol dependence 221 (2021): 108568–108568.</ref> The limited presence and access to comprehensive care for addiction poses a barrier for recovery for many, particularly those hailing from lower socioeconomic backgrounds.<ref>Saloner, Brendan, and Benjamin Le Cook. "Blacks And Hispanics Are Less Likely Than Whites To Complete Addiction Treatment, Largely Due To Socioeconomic Factors." HEALTH AFFAIRS 32, no. 1 (2013): 135–145.</ref>

==== Role of language ====
Stigma founded in societal preconceptions about substance dependence often perpetuates discrimination against those with [[Substance use disorder]] (SUD).<ref name=":10">{{Cite journal|last1=Kelly|first1=John F.|last2=Saitz|first2=Richard|last3=Wakeman|first3=Sarah|date=2016-01-02|title=Language, Substance Use Disorders, and Policy: The Need to Reach Consensus on an "Addiction-ary"|journal=Alcoholism Treatment Quarterly|volume=34|issue=1|pages=116–123|doi=10.1080/07347324.2016.1113103|s2cid=146767164|issn=0734-7324}}</ref> How language regarding SUD is framed plays an important role in mediating stigma experienced by those with the condition, which can consequently shape critical outcomes for this population such as treatment contact, social isolation, and attitudes towards healthcare providers.<ref name=":10" /> Shifting towards person-first language has been emphasized in healthcare provider circles to mitigate such stigma. For instance, as opposed to saying "former addict" or "reformed addict", the [[National Institute on Drug Abuse]] (NIDA) recommends language such as "person in recovery" or "person who previously used drugs" to separate the problem from the individual.<ref name=":11">{{Cite journal|last1=Brener|first1=Loren|last2=von Hippel|first2=William|last3=von Hippel|first3=Courtney|last4=Resnick|first4=Ilyse|last5=Treloar|first5=Carla|date=September 2010|title=Perceptions of discriminatory treatment by staff as predictors of drug treatment completion: Utility of a mixed methods approach|journal=Drug and Alcohol Review|volume=29|issue=5|pages=491–497|doi=10.1111/j.1465-3362.2010.00173.x|pmid=20887572|issn=0959-5236}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Rastegar|first=Darius A.|title=Overview of Substance Use Disorder Treatment|date=August 2020|work=ASAM Handbook of Addiction Medicine|pages=29–42|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/med/9780197506172.003.0003|isbn=978-0-19-750617-2}}</ref><ref name=":14">{{Cite web|date=2021-04-08|title=Words Matter - Terms to Use and Avoid When Talking About Addiction|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/nidamed-medical-health-professionals/health-professions-education/words-matter-terms-to-use-avoid-when-talking-about-addiction|access-date=2021-05-12|website=National Institute on Drug Abuse|language=en}}</ref> The NIDA additionally applies a similar framework to terminology such as "clean" or "dirty" to denote whether or not someone is actively using as they cite the former vocabulary holds punitive connotations.<ref name=":14" /><ref name=":15">{{Cite journal|last=Saitz|first=Richard|date=January 2016|title=International Statement Recommending Against the Use of Terminology That Can Stigmatize People|journal=Journal of Addiction Medicine|volume=10|issue=1|pages=1–2|doi=10.1097/adm.0000000000000178|pmid=26588846|s2cid=32717513|issn=1932-0620}}</ref> Moreover, SUD policy reform advocates report language adjacent to SUD can misconstrue associated medical treatment practices which in turn poses barriers to expanded harm reduction efforts from being adopted.<ref name=":15" /> An example of this provided in a 2017 executive memorandum from The National Prevention Council was a recommendation to wean usage of "opioid substitution replacement therapy" which many believe falsely alludes that an individual is substituting their addiction for another (i.e. from heroin to methadone) to "opioid agonist therapy".<ref name=":11" /><ref name=":15" />

==== Drugs and HIV infection ====
Among injecting drug users, the incidence of [[HIV]] infection is higher than among other drug addicts, however punitive and discriminatory measures against drug addicts are not able to eliminate either the spread of drug addiction or HIV. Researchers say that around 90% of people that choose to inject drugs have missed prior opportunities for HIV testing that were provided.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stulpin|first1=Caitlyn|date=20 February 2020|title=90% of injection drug users miss opportunities for HIV or HCV testing|work=Healio News|agency=Infections Disease News|url=https://www.healio.com/news/infectious-disease/20200220/90-of-injection-drug-users-miss-opportunities-for-hiv-or-hcv-testing}}</ref>

== Regional patterns ==

=== Africa ===
Africa has an estimated number 28 million substance users.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal | vauthors = Budambula V, Matoka C, Ouma J, Ahmed AA, Otieno MF, Were T | title = Socio-demographic and sexual practices associated with HIV infection in Kenyan injection and non-injection drug users | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 193 | date = January 2018 | pmid = 29378631 | pmc = 5789578 | doi = 10.1186/s12889-018-5100-y }}</ref> This number is impacted by the rising availability of injection-based drugs such as heroin, cocaine, and methamphetamines.<ref name=":0" /> Socio-demographic factors are often primary determinants of the health status of drug users.<ref name=":0" /> These factors contribute to individual drug use behaviors such as the sharing of needles and the solicitation of sex in exchange for police protection or more drugs.<ref name=":0" /> Nutritional status, family support, stigma/discrimination, adherence to medication, and recovery from addiction are also impacted by these socio-demographic factors.<ref name=":0" /> Research shows that the majority of drug users transition from the use of non-injection substances to injection substances or use both simultaneously.<ref name=":0" />

==== Kenya ====
In Kenya there is a link between injection-related discrimination, mental health, physical health, and the quality of life for those who inject drugs.<ref name=":02">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mburu G, Ayon S, Tsai AC, Ndimbii J, Wang B, Strathdee S, Seeley J | title = 'Who has ever loved a drug addict? It's a lie. They think a 'teja' is as bad person': multiple stigmas faced by women who inject drugs in coastal Kenya | journal = Harm Reduction Journal | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 29 | date = May 2018 | pmid = 29801494 | pmc = 5970466 | doi = 10.1186/s12954-018-0235-9 }}</ref> The rates of discrimination are linked to higher levels of psychological distress and risk behaviors.<ref name=":02" /> Women in Kenya account for 10% of drug users.<ref name=":02" /> These women tend to experience the regular discrimination faced by drug users in addition to gender related discrimination.<ref name=":02" /> Levels of discrimination are often higher for those that are also HIV positive.<ref name=":02" />

==== Tanzania ====
The Tanzanian government initiated support for substance-dependence treatment rehabilitation in the latter 20th century, with the Ministry of Health administering the Treatnet II center network to oversee this care.<ref>United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime. (March 2017). Prevention of Drug Use and Treatment of Drug Use Disorders in Rural Settings. UNODC.</ref> Treatment centers and [[harm reduction]] efforts in Tanzania have come into conflict with recent discourse from politicians, such as President [[John Magufuli]], who established the nation's war on drugs in early 2017.<ref name=":5">{{Cite thesis|title=The War on Drugs and Social Policy in Tanzania: Crackdowns, Prohibition and Control|url=http://ruor.uottawa.ca/handle/10393/41209|publisher=Université d'Ottawa / University of Ottawa|date=2020-10-13|degree=Thesis|doi=10.20381/ruor-25433|language=en|first=Dane|last=Degenstein}}</ref> Calling for the arrest of anyone involved in narcotics, Magufuli's stance is distinct from growing harm reduction pathways established in [[sub-Saharan Africa]] in the early decades of 2000.<ref name=":5" /> This wave of criminalization policy aims to redress the issue of those who use being primarily being targeted by law enforcement, rather than other individuals involved in the trafficking schema.<ref>Domasa, Sylivester 2018 'Tanzania: demand for drugs soars across Tanzania,' All Africa, published online March 27, 2018. <nowiki>http://allafrica.com/stories/201803270668.html</nowiki></ref> Tanzania's policing of injection drug use has encouraged both consumers and traffickers to further ingratiate themselves in the nation's black market, with injection drug users consequently being more likely to be involved in sex work and other illicit trafficking, rather than engage in traditional employment opportunities which risk greater exposure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Lambdin|first1=Barrot H.|last2=Lorvick|first2=Jennifer|last3=Mbwambo|first3=Jessie K.|last4=Rwegasha|first4=John|last5=Hassan|first5=Saria|last6=Lum|first6=Paula|last7=Kral|first7=Alex H.|date=July 2017|title=Prevalence and predictors of HCV among a cohort of opioid treatment patients in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania|url= |journal=International Journal of Drug Policy|volume=45|pages=64–69|doi=10.1016/j.drugpo.2017.05.043|pmid=28628854|pmc=6166640|issn=0955-3959}}</ref> Populations that exist at this intersection, for instance, Tanzanian women sex workers who engage in injection drug use, are alienated from utilizing risk reduction interventions due to fear of arrest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Mark L.|last2=McCurdy|first2=Sheryl A.|last3=Atkinson|first3=John S.|last4=Kilonzo|first4=Gad P.|last5=Leshabari|first5=M. T.|last6=Ross|first6=Michael W.|date=2006-09-27|title=Differences in HIV Risk Behaviors by Gender in a Sample of Tanzanian Injection Drug Users|journal=AIDS and Behavior|volume=11|issue=1|pages=137–144|doi=10.1007/s10461-006-9102-x|pmid=17004117|s2cid=36833665|issn=1090-7165}}</ref>

Low-income, urban, young men which are the most likely populace to be recruited to illicit substance trafficking due to lack of economic opportunity otherwise, have been highly scrutinized under recent waves of drug criminalization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=McCurdy|first1=S. A.|last2=Williams|first2=M. L.|last3=Kilonzo|first3=G. P.|last4=Ross|first4=M. W.|last5=Leshabari|first5=M. T.|date=June 2005|title=Heroin and HIV risk in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania: Youth hangouts, mageto and injecting practices|journal=AIDS Care|volume=17|issue=sup1|pages=65–76|doi=10.1080/09540120500120930|pmid=16096119|s2cid=38646631|issn=0954-0121}}</ref> Substance use ranging from marijuana to heroin is prohibited and a record denoting arrest for such use highly influences subsequent employment outcomes after time served for these individuals, which can ultimately be deleterious to expanding economic mobility within the communities they hail from.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=McCurdy|first1=Sheryl|last2=Kaduri|first2=Pamela|date=2016-04-02|title=The political economy of heroin and crack cocaine in Tanzania|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/action/showCitFormats?doi=10.1080/03056244.2016.1170678|journal=Review of African Political Economy|language=en|volume=43|issue=148|pages=312–319|doi=10.1080/03056244.2016.1170678|issn=0305-6244|s2cid=156730875}}</ref>

A study published in the ''Review of African Political Economy'' notes that commerce and political corruption in Tanzania have promulgated crack cocaine consumption and flash-blood practices, or blood sharing between substance users after recent injections, specifically among poor youth in urban centers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=McCurdy|first1=Sheryl A.|last2=Ross|first2=Michael W.|last3=Kilonzo|first3=Gad Paul|last4=Leshabari|first4=M.T.|last5=Williams|first5=Mark L.|date=April 2006|title=HIV/AIDS and injection drug use in the neighborhoods of Dar es Salaam, Tanzania|journal=Drug and Alcohol Dependence|volume=82|pages=S23–S27|doi=10.1016/s0376-8716(06)80004-9|pmid=16769441|issn=0376-8716}}</ref>

=== Asia ===
==== India ====
Narcotic substance consumption is prohibited in [[India]] by the Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Bill inducted in 1985, which also levies punitive measures on adjacent activities such as production or vending of such substances.<ref>{{Citation|last=Daniel|first=Heilmann|title=Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances|date=June 2010|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/law:epil/9780199231690/e1069|encyclopedia=Max Planck Encyclopedia of Public International Law|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-923169-0|access-date=2021-05-11}}</ref> Possession of a controlled substance can result in punishment ranging from a $136.21 USD fine and half a year imprisonment to $121,261 USD and twenty years imprisonment, depending on whether the amount identified is considered small or commercial.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal |author=П.М. Мазуркин |date=2013 |volume=2 |issue=2 |script-title=ru:ДИНАМИКА АЛЬФА-АКТИВНОСТИ ОБРАЗЦА 239PU В РАЗЛИЧНЫХ ШКАЛАХ ВРЕМЕНИ |journal=Science and World |doi=10.18411/a-2017-023}}</ref> Certain crimes outlined by the Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Bill are also eligible for the death penalty, and while cases involving marijuana have been charged with capital punishment in the past, they tend to be successfully appealed in higher courts.<ref>{{Cite web|date=May 9, 2012|title=Mandatory death penalty provision may be dropped from NDPS Act|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/mandatory-death-penalty-provision-may-be-dropped-from-ndps-act/articleshow/13059105.cms|access-date=2021-05-11|website=The Times of India|language=en}}</ref> This legislation is heavily influenced by a coordinated United Nations effort throughout the latter twentieth century to stymie international drug trafficking.<ref>{{Cite book |date=1999 |chapter=Extent of drug abuse |title=Global Illicit Drug Trends 1999 |location=New York |publisher=United Nations Office on Drug Control and Crime Prevention |doi=10.18356/390ac872-en |isbn=9789210041188}}</ref>

According to the [[International Drug Policy Consortium]], India's Narcotics Control Bureau, which executes the various facets of the Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Bill, has encountered criticism for the legislation's stringent measures which have limited access to pain-relief medication, specifically the prescription of opiates for post-operative patients.<ref>International Narcotics Control Board (5 March 2014), INCB encourages States to consider the abolition of the death penalty for drug-related offences, Press release, <nowiki>http://www.incb.org/documents/Publications/</nowiki> PressRelease/PR2014/press_release_050314.pdf</ref> Bill revisions in response have expanded access to such substances, like methadone, to be distributed through recognized care providers, and members of parliaments have subsequently pushed for expanded bill protections for marijuana use, which has not gained traction.<ref>Seshata, The Complicated History of Cannabis in the Islamic World, Mar 25, 2016, <nowiki>https://prohbtd.com/the-complicatedhistory-of-cannabis-in-the-islamic-world</nowiki>.</ref> Language cited as demeaning within the 2012 National Policy on Drugs and Psychotropic Substances regarding harm reduction pipelines such as clean needle programs, referring to such as "shooting galleries," have posed barriers to preventing comorbidities such as HIV which are prevalent among injection substance users in India.<ref name=":1" /> This poses an issue in states such as Punjab where over 20% of injection substance users are also infected with HIV.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Dorabjee|first1=Jimmy|last2=Samson|first2=Luke|date=March 2000|title=A multi-centre rapid assessment of injecting drug use in India|journal=International Journal of Drug Policy|volume=11|issue=1–2|pages=99–112|doi=10.1016/s0955-3959(99)00058-4|pmid=10699547|issn=0955-3959}}</ref>

==== Philippines ====
{{See also|Extrajudicial killings and forced disappearances in the Philippines}}
In the Philippines, the government's [[Philippine drug war|war on drugs]] has led to allegations of killings and other human rights violations by the [[Philippine National Police]] against drug suspects.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Mogato|first1=Manuel|last2=Baldwin|first2=Clare|date=2017-04-18|title=Special Report: Police describe kill rewards, staged crime scenes in Duterte's drug war|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-philippines-duterte-police-specialrep-idUSKBN17K1F4|access-date=2021-10-16}}</ref>

This has led the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] to adopt a resolution urging the Philippine government to set up an investigation into mass killings during the war on drugs.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2019-07-11|title=UN Human Rights Council votes to probe Philippines drug war deaths|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/united-nations-investigation-philippines-drug-deaths-1.5209238|url-status=live|access-date=2021-10-16|website=CBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712032012/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/united-nations-investigation-philippines-drug-deaths-1.5209238 |archive-date=2019-07-12 }}</ref>

==== Vietnam ====
Drug control strategy in modern [[Vietnam]] was first formally introduced in 1990 around the cause of eradicating "social evils," in reference to substance use.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |entry=Vu Quang Minh |date=2013-12-01 |encyclopedia=Who's Who |publisher=Oxford University Press |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.257599|title=Vu Quang Minh, Director-General, Economic Affairs Department, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Vietnam, since 2014 }}</ref> Such policies were inspired by the UN, and specifically, its International Drug Conventions which took placed from the latter 1960s to 1997.<ref>2005. Vietnam country profile. Hanoi, Vietnam: United Nations Office on Drug and Crime (UNODC) Country Office Vietnam.</ref> Ordinances and violation measures were propositioned by the [[National Assembly (Vietnam)|Vietnamese National Assembly]] in this legislation to mandate compulsory treatment for substance users, rather than subject them to prison.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last1=Vuong|first1=Thu|last2=Ali|first2=Robert|last3=Baldwin|first3=Simon|last4=Mills|first4=Stephen|date=July 2012|title=Drug policy in Vietnam: A decade of change?|journal=International Journal of Drug Policy|volume=23|issue=4|pages=319–326|doi=10.1016/j.drugpo.2011.11.005|pmid=22206713|issn=0955-3959}}</ref> High input in mandatory treatment centers has resulted in a tendency for there to be more patients at treatment centers than can be handled, thus limiting access to rehabilitation for these individuals.<ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last1=Nguyen Ha|first1=Pham|last2=Pharris|first2=Anastasia|last3=Huong|first3=Nguyen Thanh|last4=Thi Kim Chuc|first4=Nguyen|last5=Brugha|first5=Ruairi|last6=Thorson|first6=Anna|date=2010-08-30|title=The evolution of HIV policy in Vietnam: from punitive control measures to a more rights-based approach|url= |journal=Global Health Action|volume=3|issue=1|pages=4625|doi=10.3402/gha.v3i0.4625|pmid=20824159|pmc=2932461|issn=1654-9716}}</ref> Harm reduction measures such as clean needles and condom access have been introduced throughout the 2000s at a national level to address the prevalence of HIV and HCV among drug users.<ref name=":3" /> Inconsistencies between the Ordinance on HIVAIDS which outlines such harm reduction practices, and the Drug Law of 2000, which prohibits the distribution of materials like needles, has made provincial adoption of harm reduction institutions, like syringe exchanges, challenging.<ref>World Bank. (2011). Evaluation of epidemiological impact of harm reduction programs on HIV in Vietnam</ref>

While Vietnamese policy leaders generally veer towards addressing substance use as a medical issue, rather than criminal activity, having decriminalized many substances since 2009, the Ordinance of Administrative Violation continues to classify illicit substance consumption as a crime.<ref name=":2" /> Consequently, at a local level, substance users remain eligible to be charged by law enforcement and subjected to forced labor treatment centers that are comparable to detention.<ref name=":4">WHO. (2009). Assessment of compulsory treatment of people who use drugs in Cambodia, China, Malaysia and Vietnam: An application of selected human rights principles. WHO Western Pacific Region.</ref> Thus, many substance users do not access harm reduction institutions out of fear of being identified by law enforcement and placed in these conditions.<ref name=":4" />


=== Europe ===

==== Sweden ====
Narcotic substance use is criminalized in [[Sweden]], with drug offenses holding punishments ranging from fines to six months imprisonment.<ref>European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction (2019), Sweden, Country Drug Report 2019, Publications Office of the European Union, Luxembourg.</ref> To apprehend substance users, law enforcement is permitted to conduct urine testing on the basis of suspicion, rather than wholly requiring a public disturbance.<ref name=":6">Olsson, B., C. Adamsson-Wahren, and S. Byqvist. 2001. Det tunga narkotikamissbrukets omfattning i Sverige 1998 (Heavy drug use in Sweden 1998). The Swedish Council for Information on Alcohol and Other Drugs, CAN. Stockholm.</ref> Such protocol is justified by lawmakers as a way to expand early intervention for substance users to rehabilitation channels, but legal advocates have challenged such practices for infringing upon personal freedoms.<ref name=":6" /><ref name=":7">{{Cite journal|last1=Lenke|first1=Leif|last2=Olsson|first2=Boerje|date=2002-07-01|title=Swedish Drug Policy in the Twenty-First Century: A Policy Model Going Astray|journal=The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science|language=en|volume=582|issue=1|pages=64–79|doi=10.1177/000271620258200105|s2cid=154598556|issn=0002-7162}}</ref> Diversion to court-ordered treatment programs rather than criminalization has been expanded in response during the early 21st century, however, there are disparities in representation in such programs.<ref name=":7" /> For example, substance users found in violation who belong to the top third Swedish wealth bracket are twice as likely to be admitted into a treatment program rather than imprisoned than compared to an individual who committed a similar offense but belongs to the bottom two-thirds of the wealth bracket.<ref name=":7" /> Moreover, while those with substance dependence can apply to their local welfare administrator for rehabilitative services, this process is selective despite being less costly than long-term imprisonment for an associated drug-related crime.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gould|first=Arthur|date=October 1998|title=Book Reviews: Tim Boekhout van Solinge: The Swedish Drug Control System. Amsterdam: University of Amsterdam Centre for Drug Research, 1997|journal=Acta Sociologica|volume=41|issue=4|pages=402–404|doi=10.1177/000169939804100419|s2cid=143683007|issn=0001-6993}}</ref>

Sweden has faced criticism for having harsher drug policies and less accessible rehabilitative programs for substance users than peer Nordic nations which are moving towards [[drug liberalization]].<ref name=":7" /> Many cite this for why Sweden has rising substance-related mortality in the 21st century, for instance, having 157 overdose deaths in 2006 compared to the [[Netherlands]] which had a little over a hundred despite having a population close to double the size.<ref>UNODC: Sweden's successful drug policy, 2007, pp. 9–12</ref> Zero-tolerance policies are also in place for those who drive under the influence of an illicit substance.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Medium- and long-term debt prospects in Eastern Europe |date=1991 |title=East-West Financial Relations: Current Problems and Future Prospects |pages=77–100| publisher=Cambridge University Press |doi=10.1017/cbo9780511751868.005 |isbn=978-0-521-39530-4}}</ref>

=== North America ===

==== Canada ====

In Vancouver, Canada, there have been efforts to reduce opioid-related deaths. An article published by the Canadian Medical Association Journal discusses new efforts to create safe injection sites for people struggling with opioid addiction. Vancouver politicians created these sites for people to safely use drugs that they are addicted to without the risk of infection or prosecution by the police. These safe injection sites provide sterilized needles to limit the reuse of needles that lead to the spread of AIDS and other diseases.<ref name="jones" /> Drug addicts in Vancouver have been discriminated against on numerous occasions. Mothers who are said to be drug addicts have had their children taken away, as they are thought to be unfit mothers. These women have a hard time getting jobs because employers might not want to hire someone who they believe are drug addicts. Women have started a union for drug users in Vancouver to aid them with housing and education to help them get back on their feet.

==== United States ====
[[File:States that suspend driver's licenses for drug offenses.svg|thumb|The Prison Policy Initiative cites that the criminalization of drug use in the United States can limit personal daily activities for those who may use substances, even if it is done in a safe, recreational manner.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ending automatic driver's license suspensions for drug offenses|url=https://www.prisonpolicy.org/driving/|access-date=2021-03-30|website=www.prisonpolicy.org|language=en}}</ref>]]
[[War on drugs|The War on Drugs]], which formalized in the 1970s with the Nixon administration, has disparately affected communities of color in the United States.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Miron|first1=Jeffrey|last2=Partin|first2=Erin|date=2021-04-03|title=Ending the War on Drugs Is an Essential Step Toward Racial Justice|journal=The American Journal of Bioethics|volume=21|issue=4|pages=1–3|doi=10.1080/15265161.2021.1895590|pmid=33825624|s2cid=233174284|issn=1526-5161}}</ref> Substantial punitive measures exist for illicit possession, whether that be in the context of use, trafficking, or selling, with length of incarceration scaling up with repeat offenses.<ref>{{Cite ssrn |last=Tuttle|first=Cody|date=2019|title=Racial Disparities in Federal Sentencing: Evidence from Drug Mandatory Minimums |ssrn=3080463}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite journal|last=Bjerk|first=David|date=2017-01-01|title=Mandatory Minimums and the Sentencing of Federal Drug Crimes|url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/10.1086/690205|journal=The Journal of Legal Studies|volume=46|issue=1|pages=93–128|doi=10.1086/690205|hdl=10419/161167|s2cid=157903931|issn=0047-2530}}</ref> Charges can go up to life without parole for third-time offenses related to opiates such as [[fentanyl]].<ref name=":8" /> Three-quarters of those imprisoned for fentanyl today are people of color, which directly corresponds to Black and Latin populations being disproportionately policed for drug-related crimes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Santoro|first1=Taylor N|last2=Santoro|first2=Jonathan D|date=2018-12-14|title=Racial Bias in the US Opioid Epidemic: A Review of the History of Systemic Bias and Implications for Care|url= |journal=Cureus|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e3733|doi=10.7759/cureus.3733|pmid=30800543|pmc=6384031|issn=2168-8184}}</ref> This additionally infringes upon voting eligibility among substance-using populations, as more extreme drug charges hold felony status which revokes voting rights in a majority of states.<ref>McLeod, A., White, I.K., and Gavin, A.R. (2003). "The Locked Ballot Box: The Impact of State Criminal Disenfranchisement Laws on African American Voting Behavior and Implications for Reform." Journal of Social Policy and the Law, 11, (1), 66-88.</ref> Drug criminalization moreover operates within the deportation pipeline in the US, with drug charges making all individuals without citizenship eligible for deportation.<ref name=":9">{{Cite book|last=Barillas|first=Wilber A.|title=Collateral Damage: Drug Enforcement & Its Impact on the Deportation of Legal Permanent Residents|date=2014-04-16|publisher=Boston College Law School|oclc=876889955}}</ref> This includes marijuana-related charges which have constituted over ten thousand deportations from 2012 to 2013, often severing families and communities.<ref name=":9" /> While statewide measures to legalize marijuana have gained traction throughout 2010, individuals of color have been less likely to receive post-carceral clemency for these charges due to barriers to legal advocacy.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Report: The War on Marijuana in Black and White|url=https://www.aclu.org/report/report-war-marijuana-black-and-white|access-date=2021-05-12|website=American Civil Liberties Union|language=en}}</ref>

Substance dependence disorder advocates have criticized the use of demeaning language regarding the condition in criminal litigation to leverage character assault against defendants or victims who have or presumed to have the condition.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Freeman-Wilson|first1=Karen P.|last2=Tuttle|first2=Robert|last3=Weinstein|first3=Susan|title=Ethical considerations for judges and attorneys in drug court|date=2001|publisher=National Drug Court Institute|oclc=57750255}}</ref> A prominent example of this is the [[trial of Derek Chauvin]], the former Minneapolis police officer convicted of [[murder of George Floyd|murdering George Floyd]], whose legal defense asserted substance use as a potential [[cause of death]], rather than the asphyxiation incurred from Chauvin.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Derek Chauvin defense expert blames heart disease and drug use for George Floyd's death|language=en-US|newspaper=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2021/04/14/derek-chauvin-trial-2/|access-date=2021-05-12|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

Discrimination against people who use an illegal substance is very common in the workplace, a familiar example happens when employers give random drug test to see if the employee will pass it.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|title=Patients with Addiction Need Treatment - Not Stigma|url=https://www.asam.org/resources/publications/magazine/read/article/2015/12/15/patients-with-a-substance-use-disorder-need-treatment---not-stigma|access-date=2018-09-28|website=www.asam.org}}</ref> However, according to the [[Rehabilitation Act of 1973]], employers are supposed to ensure that alcoholics and other drug addicts get help and the accommodations that they need. The Disability Discrimination Act of 1995 may not cover employees who are using drugs. According to Davies Robert, "an employee who claims that addiction is a disability is mistaken, as alcoholism and drug addictions are specifically excluded from the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (DDA). But severe depression caused by or related to a person's alcoholism or gambling addiction, for example, can be covered by the DDA if the effect on day-to-day activities lasts for 12 months or longer. Claims alleging discrimination then become possible".<ref>(www.peoplemanagement.co.uk/law, Davies, Robert  2008 March 20)</ref> The most common discrimination in the workplace is that during the interview process some employers overlook the interviewer's qualifications because they know they have or had a problem with drugs, and make a decision solely based on their addiction when the interviewer could be well qualified for the position. This is against the Discrimination  Act 1995  (DDA). This act has counted addiction and alcoholism as a disability, so therefore addiction is protected under this act. Through the years, this act has declined in defending these individuals. According to "Alcoholism & Drug Abuse Weekly", Miranda John states, "the strength of these protections has been eroded in recent years as a result of court decisions and the lack of a strong constituency advocating the rights of addicts and alcoholics." (John, De Miranda, "Discrimination Against Drug Addicts and Alcohol Still Persists." (Alcoholism and Drug Abuse Weekly, Vol 13. Issue 47 P.5, 2001, December 12) The lack of job opportunities and treatment for drug addicts often results in relapses or in jail.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2014-12-08|title=Employers guide to Addiction {{!}} How to get help|url=https://www.addictionhelper.com/addiction/employers/|access-date=2021-01-20|website=Addiction Helper|language=en-US}}</ref> Nathan Kim and his associates once conducted a study on the HIV status of people who inject drugs and found that the HIV rate in those individuals in San Francisco increased by 16.1% from the year 2009 when the HIV rate was 64.4%, to 80.5% in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=Nathan|last2=Welty|first2=Susie|last3=Reza|first3=Tania|last4=Sears|first4=David|last5=McFarland|first5=Willi|last6=Raymond|first6=Henry F.|date=1 June 2019|title=Undiagnosed and Untreated HIV Infection Among Persons Who Inject Drugs: Results of Three National HIV Behavioral Surveillance Surveys, San Francisco, 2009–2015|journal=AIDS and Behavior|volume=23|issue=6|pages=1586–1589|doi=10.1007/s10461-018-2284-1|pmid=30259347|s2cid=52843973}}</ref>

